{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"LzH7W3mDrTWa"},"source":["# CAP 4633C — Assignment 2\n","**Student:** Jessica Vargas  \n"],"id":"LzH7W3mDrTWa"},{"cell_type":"code","metadata":{"id":"bPu3EgrLrTWd","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1774353098026,"user_tz":240,"elapsed":2066,"user":{"displayName":"Jessica Vargas","userId":"04622878135586132667"}}},"execution_count":1,"outputs":[],"source":["# Imports\n","import numpy as np\n","import pandas as pd\n","\n","from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, GridSearchCV, KFold\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n","from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline\n","from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression\n","from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report, recall_score, precision_score, f1_score, make_scorer\n","\n","from sklearn import datasets\n"],"id":"bPu3EgrLrTWd"},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"xAmzhjbJrTWf"},"source":["## Question 1 (20 points)\n","Based on the article **\"Application of Binary Logistic Regression in Clinical Research\"**.\n","\n","### 1a) Difference between binary logistic regression and ordinal logistic regression\n","**Binary logistic regression** is used when the outcome has **two categories** (ex: disease present vs absent).  \n","**Ordinal logistic regression** is used when the outcome has **ordered categories** (ex: poor < fair < good < very good < excellent).  \n","\n","**Key difference:** Binary logistic predicts one logit for a **binary** outcome; ordinal logistic models an **ordered** outcome (commonly via cumulative probabilities / proportional odds).\n","\n","### 1a1) Example of ordinal logistic regression (online)\n","**Example:** UCLA IDRE example where the outcome is **soda size** (small, medium, large, extra large). The response is ordered, so ordinal logistic regression is appropriate.\n","\n","### 1b) Meaning of equation (4) after plugging Age and Smoking Status\n","When you plug a person’s **Age** and **Smoking status (0/1)** into equation (4), you obtain a **number** that equals the **log-odds (logit)** of having CVD.\n","\n","- Let **p = P(CVD = 1 | age, smoking)**.\n","- The **logit** is:  \n","  **logit(p) = log( p / (1 − p) )**.\n","- If you exponentiate it, you get the **odds**:  \n","  **odds = p/(1−p) = exp(logit(p))**.\n","- You can convert to a probability:  \n","  **p = 1 / (1 + exp(−logit(p)))**.\n","\n","### 1c) Odds ratio (OR) meaning + examples\n","The **odds ratio** compares **odds** between two situations.\n","- For a one-unit increase in a predictor X, **OR = exp(beta)**.\n","- For a 0/1 predictor (ex: smoker vs non-smoker), **OR** compares the odds for group 1 over group 0 while holding other predictors fixed.\n","\n","### 1d) Can predictors be continuous or categorical?\n","Yes — predictors (independent variables) can be **continuous** or **categorical**.\n","**Class example:** In our Default-style examples, a continuous predictor like **balance** and a categorical predictor like **student (Yes/No)** can both be used in logistic regression (categorical is represented with dummy variables).\n"],"id":"xAmzhjbJrTWf"},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"JtCDOMRDrTWg"},"source":["## Question 2 (40 points) — Bank Deposit dataset\n","\n"],"id":"JtCDOMRDrTWg"},{"cell_type":"code","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":226},"id":"lYISVz4RrTWg","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1774353193691,"user_tz":240,"elapsed":211,"user":{"displayName":"Jessica Vargas","userId":"04622878135586132667"}},"outputId":"83ced429-4a1e-4fa7-8027-9b958eff0114"},"execution_count":2,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["   age  campaign  emp.var.rate  cons.price.idx  cons.conf.idx  euribor3m  \\\n","0   30         2          -1.8          92.893          -46.2      1.313   \n","1   39         4           1.1          93.994          -36.4      4.855   \n","2   25         1           1.4          94.